title: Manhattan: Central Park - 5th Avenue - 69th Street

text:
5th Avenue, east side, at E. 69th Street, showing private dwellings at both the N.E. and S.E. corners. These in order are (or were) the Adolph Lewisohn (No.881), the E.H. Harriman (No. 1 E. 69th Street), the Ogden Mills (No.877) and the Daniel J. Leary (No. 876) homes.

The N.Y. Herald Tribune of Sunday, June 18, 1939 carries a photo and an article reporting the details of the proposed replacement with an apartment house of the Harriman and possibly the Lewisohn homes. Sir John Mactaggart, a Scottish builder purchased the former 5 years ago and is about to proceed with plans for this site.

View 2 shows only the Lewisohn and Harriman homes while No.3 features 'only the latter.

Views 1 and 3: July 21, 1937
View 2: April 23, 1938

P.L.Sperr

(1)

1-7 East 69th Street, at, adjoining and east of the N.E. corner of Fifth Ave. The 5-story mansion directly at the corner is No. 1, while the 3-story former garage has no number. The vacant lots formerly were Nos. 3-7 and are at the rear of the former Marshall Field residence (Nos. 4-8 East 70th Street inclusive), where they formed a garden. This has lately been sold (See The New York Times- March 23, 1937) and the purchaser's will erect two 12-story apartment houses here.

March 29, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)

The same. The 5-story mansion, No. 1 East 69th Street, was the Harriman home.

P. L. Sperr.

East 69th Street, north side, east from Fifth Ave., showing the Harriman home, No. 1 East 69th Street, and a garage at its rear. East of the latter is the Marshall Field garden, occupying the sites of Nos. 3 to 7 inclusive. Upon same, will rise a new 12-story apartment house; one half of a twin unit project.

July 21, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
A detail of same, showing the 3-story garage at the rear of No. 1.

July 21, 1937.
